[1]
Date: Thu 12 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Wed 11 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L11725665.htm>

Turkey: Possible Influence of Tamiflu Treatment and Winter Weather
------------------------------------------------------------------
Turkey stepped up efforts on Wednesday 11 Jan 2006 to halt outbreaks
of bird flu in both people and poultry, but U.N. experts said the
virus could become firmly established and threaten neighboring
countries. Experts said the H5N1 avian influenza virus could become
more active in the colder months in affected regions, and spread in
east Asia as people slaughter chickens for Lunar New Year
celebrations. It will cost international donors about UDS 1.4 billion
to finance the next phase of the global campaign against the virus,
including gearing up veterinary services and preparing expert teams
for quick deployment to outbreaks, a senior United Nations expert
said. But Dr. David Nabarro, U.N. senior coordinator for avian
influenza, said he was confident delegates to next week's bird flu
conference in Beijing would pledge the needed amount.
H5N1 has been found in wild birds and poultry in a third of Turkish
provinces. It has killed at least 2 children and infected more than a
dozen people in little more than a week. While overall very few
people have been infected -- about 150 [currently 148 according to
WHO] with 78 killed in 6 countries --- scientists fear the virus
could mutate into a form that can spread easily between humans,
causing a pandemic.
World Health Organization doctors said there was no sign of
human-to-human transmission in Turkey. They called for calm and said
there was no reason for tourists not to visit Turkey. The virus has
rapidly infected birds in about 30 out of 81 provinces in Turkey,
including Ankara, Istanbul and the tourism region near the Aegean
coast. Authorities, criticized for an initial slow response, have
killed more than 300 000 birds.
Turkish officials have been stressing that relatively few people
there have died, compared to Asia, where H5N1 has had about a
50-percent mortality rate. WHO said there is no evidence the virus
has changed greatly and says patients have been infected by close
contact with sick poultry -- in most cases children playing with
birds or helping families kill them. "Compared to the numbers in
Asia, we do not have too many deaths at the moment," said Dr. Guenael
Rodier, head of the WHO mission to Turkey, told a news conference.
"We need to investigate this and to see if the use of Tamiflu has
played a role in the (smaller) numbers," he said. "I have the feeling
that what is going on in Turkey can be brought under control
relatively easily like in Asia," Rodier added. "At the moment, there
is good awareness. We will try to keep some kind of momentum on these
issues for months to come."
Winter weather is almost certainly playing a role, experts agree.
Influenza and similar viruses always become more common in winter,
even in tropical zones where temperatures do not change much, for
reasons that are not clearly understood. Authorities believe many
poor families in eastern Turkey brought their sick birds into houses
when winter hit, increasing chances of infection.
More people are likely to be infected in Asia before this month's
Lunar New Year holidays, when consumption of poultry rises, Shigeru
Omi, WHO's regional director for the Western Pacific, told
Reuters.Eating well-cooked bird meat is not a risk, but slaughtering birds is.
[Byline: Paul de Bendern and Gareth Jones]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[If it transpires that the prompt and widespread use of Tamiflu in
the treatment of patients in Turkey is responsible for the lower
mortality than in East Asia, the prospects for control of an A/H5N1
avian influenza pandemic in the human population are greatly
enhanced. - Mod.CP]
